SIMPLE: pert
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pert
<hw>Pert</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[An aphetic form of OE. &
OF. <ets>apert</ets> open, known, true, free, or impudent. See
<er>Apert</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Open; evident; apert.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lively; brisk; sprightly; smart.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Indecorously free, or presuming; saucy; bold;
impertinent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A very <xex>pert</xex> manner.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The squirrel, flippant, <qex>pert</qex>, and full of play.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pert
<hw>Pert</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To behave with pertness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Gauden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pertain</ent>⟦br⟧
